<quantity box="[713,786,656,680]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" unit="m" value="400.0">400 m</quantity>
depth (
<bibRefCitation author="Tommasi, L. R." box="[873,1060,655,680]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="1 - 50" refId="ref65269" refString="Tommasi, L. R. (1966 a) Lista dos Equinoides recentes do Brasil. Contribuicoes do Instituto Oceanografico, Serie Oceanografia Biologica, 11, 1 - 50." type="journal article" year="1966">Tommasi 1966a</bibRefCitation>
). In the present study, specimens from 
<collectingRegion box="[212,304,692,717]" country="Brazil" name="Alagoas" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Alagoas</collectingRegion>
were collected about 
<quantity box="[550,593,692,716]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" unit="m" value="2.0">2 m</quantity>
deep.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1328]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,727,752]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brito" authorityYear="1962" box="[325,568,727,752]" class="Echinoidea" family="Diadematidae" genus="Diadema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diadematoida" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ascensionis">
<emphasis box="[325,568,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Diadema ascensionis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. L. Clark" authorityYear="1925" box="[728,884,727,752]" class="Echinoidea" family="Diadematidae" genus="Diadema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diadematoida" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="antillarum">
<emphasis box="[728,884,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">D. antillarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the strongly curved valves in the tridentate pedicellariae. Since its original description, the taxonomic status of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brito" authorityYear="1962" box="[919,1083,765,788]" class="Echinoidea" family="Diadematidae" genus="Diadema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diadematoida" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ascensionis">
<emphasis box="[919,1083,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">D. ascensionis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been debated, having been considered a synonym or a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. L. Clark" authorityYear="1925" box="[629,784,799,824]" class="Echinoidea" family="Diadematidae" genus="Diadema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diadematoida" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="antillarum">
<emphasis box="[629,784,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">D. antillarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Presently it is considered a valid species, but molecular data (Lessios 2001; Lessios 
<emphasis box="[465,521,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al.</emphasis>
2001) conflict with morphology. However, several studies have found differences to support its designation as a distinct species (
<bibRefCitation author="Coppard, S. E. &amp; Campbell, A. C." box="[692,1007,871,896]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="357 - 371" refId="ref50830" refString="Coppard, S. E. &amp; Campbell, A. C. (2004) Taxonomic significance of spine morphology in the echinoid genera Diadema and Echinothrix. Invertebrate Biology, 123 (4), 357 - 371. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1744 - 7410.2004. tb 00168. x" type="journal article" year="2004">Coppard &amp; Campbell 2004</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Coppard, S. E. &amp; Campbell, A. C." box="[1020,1091,871,896]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="363 - 378" refId="ref50890" refString="Coppard, S. E. &amp; Campbell, A. C. (2006 a) Systematic significance of tridentate pedicellariae in the echinoid genera Diadema and Echinothrix. Invertebrate Biology, 125 (4), 363 - 378. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1744 - 7410.2006.00068. x" type="journal article" year="2006">2006a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Coppard, S. E. &amp; Campbell, A. C." box="[1105,1178,871,896]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="93 - 112" refId="ref50948" refString="Coppard, S. E. &amp; Campbell, A. C. (2006 b) Taxonomic significance of test morphology in the echinoid genera Diadema Gray, 1825 and Echinothrix Peters, 1853 (Echinodermata). Zoosystema, 28 (1), 93 - 112." type="journal article" year="2006">2006b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gondim, A. I. &amp; Dias, TLP &amp; Christoffersen, M. L." box="[1192,1432,871,896]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="431 - 435" refId="ref53736" refString="Gondim, A. I., Dias, TLP. &amp; Christoffersen, M. L. (2013 a) Diadema ascensionis Mortensen, 1909 (Echinodermata: Echinoidea) is not restricted to Oceanic Islands: evidence from morphological data. Brazilian Journal of Biology, 73 (2), 431 - 435. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 1519 - 69842013000200027" type="journal article" year="2013">
Gondim 
<emphasis box="[1292,1351,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al.</emphasis>
2013a
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Rodriguez, A. &amp; Hernandez, J. C. &amp; Clemente, S. &amp; Coppard, S. E." box="[151,405,908,933]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="144 - 170" refId="ref62549" refString="Rodriguez, A., Hernandez, J. C., Clemente, S. &amp; Coppard, S. E. (2013) A new species of Diadema (Echinodermata: Echinoidea: Diadematidae) from the eastern Atlantic Ocean and a neotype designation of Diadema antillarum (Philippi, 1845). Zootaxa, 3636 (1), 144 - 170. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3636.1.6" type="journal article" year="2013">
Rodríguez 
<emphasis box="[277,335,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
). Specimens studied herein, from reefs at Francês Beach (
<collectingRegion box="[1073,1170,908,933]" country="Brazil" name="Alagoas" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Alagoas</collectingRegion>
), had all the characters that permit its distinction from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. L. Clark" authorityYear="1925" box="[498,650,943,968]" class="Echinoidea" family="Diadematidae" genus="Diadema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diadematoida" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="antillarum">
<emphasis box="[498,650,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">D. antillarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the specimens from this locality were previously identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. L. Clark" authorityYear="1925" box="[184,338,980,1005]" class="Echinoidea" family="Diadematidae" genus="Diadema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diadematoida" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="antillarum">
<emphasis box="[184,338,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">D. antillarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. To distinguish these two species correctly, an accurate analysis of the pedicellariae and of the structure of the spines is necessary. We analyzed both adult and young individuals. In distinction to other sea urchins, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brito" authorityYear="1962" box="[248,412,1053,1076]" class="Echinoidea" family="Diadematidae" genus="Diadema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diadematoida" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ascensionis">
<emphasis box="[248,412,1053,1076]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">D. ascensionis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a hemicyclic apical system in all developmental stages, with the possible exception of post-larvae (not observed by us).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1328]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,399,1124,1149]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Ecological notes.</emphasis>
In the coastal reefs of Francês Beach, State of 
<collectingRegion box="[941,1036,1124,1149]" country="Brazil" name="Alagoas" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Alagoas</collectingRegion>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brito" authorityYear="1962" box="[1048,1213,1125,1148]" class="Echinoidea" family="Diadematidae" genus="Diadema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diadematoida" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ascensionis">
<emphasis box="[1048,1213,1125,1148]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">D. ascensionis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found in areas with sandy substrates or among rocks of the reef formations, in zones of clear and well-illuminated water. Both isolated and clusters of individuals were observed, dense populations occurring up to 
<quantity box="[1135,1181,1196,1220]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" unit="m" value="2.0">2 m</quantity>
depth (
<bibRefCitation author="Gondim, A. I. &amp; Dias, TLP &amp; Christoffersen, M. L." pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="431 - 435" refId="ref53736" refString="Gondim, A. I., Dias, TLP. &amp; Christoffersen, M. L. (2013 a) Diadema ascensionis Mortensen, 1909 (Echinodermata: Echinoidea) is not restricted to Oceanic Islands: evidence from morphological data. Brazilian Journal of Biology, 73 (2), 431 - 435. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 1519 - 69842013000200027" type="journal article" year="2013">
Gondim 
<emphasis box="[1371,1421,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al</emphasis>
., 2013a
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, L. &amp; Souto, C. &amp; Braga, J. &amp; Tavares, M." box="[246,487,1231,1256]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="521 - 555" refId="ref59121" refString="Martins, L., Souto, C., Braga, J. &amp; Tavares, M. (2018) Echinoidea and Holothuroidea (Echinodermata) of the Trindade and Martin Vaz Archipelago, off Brazil, with new records and remarks on taxonomy and species composition. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom, 98 (3), 521 - 555. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0025315416001569" type="journal article" year="2018">
Martins 
<emphasis box="[343,403,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al.</emphasis>
(2018)
</bibRefCitation>
observed a gregarious habit in specimens from Trindade and Martin Vaz Islands, where specimens were usually found in reef crevices during the day and moving around areas with a high percentage of green algae cover.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
